[1]
Date: Sat 6 Dec 2008
From: Deborah Briggs
<briggs@vet.k-state.edu>


Re: ProMED-mail posting 20081204.3821 "Rabies, canine, human -
Indonesia (03): (Bali)"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Regarding the decree from the Bali Governor to control a potential
canine rabies outbreak on that island by mass culling of stray dogs,
it is critical to understand that this method of disease control does
not work. Similar mass culling strategies have been used without
success on isolated islands and on land where canine rabies exists.

Many excellent examples of failed attempts at controlling canine
rabies through mass culling processes exist, for example officials on
Flores Island tried to eliminate a canine rabies outbreak 8 years ago
by killing over 500 000 dogs and yet rabies is still present on that
island. Similarly, when canine rabies spread to the region of
Sulawesi in Indonesia approximately 5 years later, mass culling of
dogs was again attempted without successfully eliminating rabies.

On the other hand, mass vaccination of dogs against rabies does work.
There are also many countrywide examples proving that when the WHO
recommendation of vaccinating 70 percent of the dog population
against rabies is applied, the spread of rabies throughout the dog
population is stopped. Excellent examples of successful programs
exist in Latin America where the Pan American Health Organization
spearheaded mass canine vaccination programs throughout the continent
resulting in a dramatic reduction in the prevalence of both canine
rabies and human rabies.

Similar success stories have been reported in Africa, for example in
Tanzania where mass canine rabies vaccination cleared rabies from the
community dog population surrounding the Serengeti region resulting
in the protection of endangered species of wildlife within the park.
When it comes to rabies, the tools to prevent the existence and
spread of this disease in dogs already exist and have been proven to
work; they only need to be utilized.

--
Dr Deborah J Briggs, Adjunct Professor, College of Veterinary Medicine,
Kansas State University, Manhattan Kansas; and
Executive Director, the Alliance for Rabies Control,
Balfour and Manson, 54 - 56 Frederick St.,
Edinburgh EH2 ILS
<briggs@vet.k-state.edu>

